7"></a><a href="#_ftnref27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Section 10 of the Legal Aid S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">entencing and Punishment of Offenders Act (LASPO) 2012 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn28"></a><a href="#_ftnref28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Public Law Project Response to Transforming Legal Aid proposals, Judicial Review Journal, Volume 18, No 3, July 2013, page 80</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn29"></a><a href="#_ftnref29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Between 1 April and 1 July 2013 there were 233 applications for except</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ional funding of which 6 were successful. Only two of these were for non-inquest cases. (Legal Action Magazine, September 2013, page 40).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn30"></a><a href="#_ftnref30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The legality of the proposed residence test for civil legal aid: joint opinion; Michael Fordham QC, Ben Jaffey, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Ravi Mehta of Blacks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tone Chambers; Judicial Review J</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ournal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, Volume 18, No 3, July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn31"></a><a href="#_ftnref31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> R (Al-Skeini) v. Secretary of State for Defence [2007] UKHL 26 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn32"></a><a href="#_ftnref32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> [2011] EWHC 2401 (Admin), [2012] 1 WLR 1389</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn33"></a><a h